Subject: Reduce wait times in Haskell tests
Message-Id: <c041ae281b757e49-0-artemis@nixos-framework>
resolution: fixed

The current Haskell tests use hard-coded sleep-for and timeouts (5-15 seconds) which make the test suite slow. Tests also wait blindly rather than checking for actual readiness.

Improvements needed:
- Poll HLS readiness more intelligently by checking for specific LSP notifications (e.g., "initialized" or "indexing complete")
- Replace hard sleep-for calls with condition-based waiting that exits early when ready
- Check *EGLOT events* buffer to verify HLS has actually processed requests before asserting results
- Add diagnostic helpers to determine why HLS isn't responding (not initialized, still indexing, etc.)
- Consider whether tests need compilation step (cabal build) before HLS can provide full functionality

Current failures in eldoc, hover, and jump-to-definition may be timing-related rather than actual config problems.
